          },
          "outcomes": [
            {
              "type": "before",
              "label": "Lesson Learned",
              "value": "\u26a0\ufe0f",
              "detail": "Don't invest in what you don't understand. Never invest money you can't afford to lose. Foundation first. Speculation \u2260 Investing."
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "number": 17,
      "type": "discussion",
      "variant": "teal",
      "content": {
        "badge": "Discussion",
        "question": "<strong>1. Foundation Check:</strong> Do you have an emergency fund and retirement savings before considering alternatives? If not, what steps should come first?<br><br><strong>2. Emotional Test:</strong> How would you feel if an alternative investment lost 50% of its value in a month? Could you avoid panic selling?<br><br><strong>3. Risk Tolerance:</strong> Which alternative investments might align with your goals and interests\u2014and what percentage would be appropriate for your situation?<br><br><strong>4. Social Pressure:</strong> How would you respond if friends pressured you to invest in a trending asset that you haven't researched?"
      },
      "headerColor": "emerald"
    },
    {
      "number": 18,
      "type": "content",
      "headerColor": "amber",
      "content": {
        "headerTitle": "Check Your Understanding",
        "layout": "check-grid",
        "layoutData": {
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "If Stock A and Gold have a correlation of -0.3, what happens to gold when Stock A falls significantly?",
              "answer": "Gold tends to rise (negative correlation means they move in opposite directions)"
            },
            {
              "number": 2,
              "question": "You need $15,000 urgently. Which is easier to convert to cash\u2014REIT shares or a rental property?",
              "answer": "REIT shares (high liquidity\u2014can sell in seconds vs. months for property)"
            },
            {
              "number": 3,
              "question": "True or False: Someone with no emergency fund should invest 20% of their savings in cryptocurrency.",
              "answer": "FALSE\u2014Foundation (emergency fund, retirement) must come first"
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "number": 19,
      "type": "content",
      "headerColor": "indigo",
      "content": {
        "headerTitle": "Key Takeaways",
        "layout": "takeaway-grid",
        "layoutData": {
          "takeaways": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "title": "Alternatives Supplement, Don't Replace",
              "description": "Keep alternatives at 10-20% maximum after establishing your foundation of index funds and emergency savings"
            },
            {
              "number": 2,
              "title": "REITs Make Real Estate Accessible",
              "description": "Get real estate exposure without needing $50K down payment or property management responsibilities"
            },
            {
              "number": 3,
              "title": "Gold = Insurance, Not Growth",
              "description": "Precious metals are inflation hedges for protection, not primary wealth-building tools. 5% maximum."
            },
            {
              "number": 4,
              "title": "Crypto = Speculation",
              "description": "Only invest what you can afford to lose completely (1-5% max). Understand the technology and risks first."
            },
            {
              "number": 5,
              "title": "Foundation First Always",
              "description": "Emergency fund and retirement accounts are non-negotiable prerequisites before exploring alternatives"
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    },
